'''Martin Saidler''' is a [[Vienna]]-born Swiss businessman and investor in internet and [[financial technology]] companies.  He has done most of his investing in central Europe, working mostly through a holding company called Centralway, and subsequently through a [[family office]] called Saidler & Co.

== Career ==
Martin Saidler was born in [[Vienna]], [[Austria]] in 1967.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schneider|first1=Katharina|title=„Die Welt braucht nicht noch eine Bank“|url=https://www.handelsblatt.com/finanzen/anlagestrategie/trends/centralway-chef-saidler-im-interview-die-welt-braucht-nicht-noch-eine-bank/19306068-all.html|publisher=Handelsblatt|language=German ||archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122053624/https://www.handelsblatt.com/finanzen/anlagestrategie/trends/centralway-chef-saidler-im-interview-die-welt-braucht-nicht-noch-eine-bank/19306068-all.html|archivedate=22 January 2018}}</ref> His mother came from [[Slovakia]] and he grew up speaking Slovak at home.<ref name=Lupa/>  He attended the [[University of Vienna]] where he studied journalism and political science.<ref name=Lupa>{{cite news|title=Martin Saidler: český Internet bude do dvou let patřit americkým firmám|url=https://www.lupa.cz/clanky/martin-saidler-cesky-internet-bude-patrit-americkym-firmam/|publisher=Lupa.cz|date=22 February 2007|language=Czech |archiveurl=http://www.lupa.cz/clanky/martin-saidler-cesky-internet-bude-patrit-americkym-firmam/|archivedate=12 January 2017}}</ref> He then moved to [[Berlin]] where in 1997 he founded the employment website Jobinteractive.com.<ref name=boersen>{{cite news|last1=Brosy|first1=Martin|title=Martin Saidler – Der erfolgreichste Online-Unternehmer der Schweiz?|url=http://www.boersenpoint.de/boersenblog/blog/martin-saidler-der-erfolgreichste-online-unternehmer-der-schweiz-1793041/||publisher=Boersenpoint|date=29 July 2016|language=German ||archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170530091312/http://www.boersenpoint.de:80/boersenblog/blog/martin-saidler-der-erfolgreichste-online-unternehmer-der-schweiz-1793041/|archivedate=30 May 2017}}</ref> In 1998, it became one of the major job portals in Germany.<ref name=boersen/> In 1999, Beisheim Holding Switzerland (BHS) acquired Jobinteractive.com.<ref name=bilanz/>  BHS combined it with other businesses in a company called Scout24.<ref name=startwerk/>  Saidler stayed with the company until around 2001, [[technology scouting|scouting]] opportunities for them in central Europe, and cashed out just before the [[dot-com bubble]] burst.<ref name=bilanz/><ref name=skinner/>

Saidler used that money, along with money from a Luxembourg fund called Incubation Capital SARL, as capital for the investment company Centralway AG, based in [[Zug]], Switzerland, and developed it into one of the largest Internet corporate groups in central Europe.<ref name=bilanz>{{cite news|last1=Kowalsky|first1=Mark|title=Centralway: Der Online-Zar in Osteuropa|url=http://www.bilanz.ch/unternehmen/centralway-der-online-zar-osteuropa|publisher=Billanz|date=9 April 2010|language=German ||archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171016014921/http://www.bilanz.ch/unternehmen/centralway-der-online-zar-osteuropa|archivedate=16 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=skinner/>  Through 2010, his investment strategy was to invest mostly in central Europe, in companies controlled by their founders that were making money and leading in their field; he would help them grow for three to four years, then seek an exit.<ref name=bilanz/>  Many of these transactions were among private companies, so the sources of investment and the amounts of money spent and earned are not known.<ref name=skinner>{{cite news|last1=Skinner|first1=Barnaby|title=Der talentierte Mr. Saidler|work=SonntagsZeitung|date=19 January 2014}}; republished on author's website, as {{cite news|title=The talented Mr. Saidler|url=http://barnabyskinner.com/journal/2014/3/11/the-talented-mr-saidler.html|date=11 March 2014 |last1=Skinner |first1=Barnaby |publisher=Barnabyskinner.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170629093857/http://barnabyskinner.com:80/journal/2014/3/11/the-talented-mr-saidler.html|archivedate=29 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hässig|first1=Lukas|title=Die Ospels und der Dreihundert-Mio-Mann|url=https://insideparadeplatz.ch/2013/12/03/die-ospels-und-der-dreihundert-mio-mann/|date=3 December 2013|language=German |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301184900/https://insideparadeplatz.ch/2013/12/03/die-ospels-und-der-dreihundert-mio-mann/|archivedate=1 March 2017}}</ref>

By 2011 Saidler determined that the market for IT companies in central Europe had become overpriced, so Centralway sold off most of its investments, stopped making new investments there, and starting looking at investments inside Switzerland,<ref name=bilanz2011>{{cite news|title=Internetpionier Saidler investiert massiv in der Schweiz||publisher=Bilanz|date=28 July 2011|language=German}}</ref>  at a time when there was a rising market of internet-based startups in Switzerland.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kowalsky|first1=Marc|title=Internetszene Schweiz: Start up!|url=http://www.bilanz.ch/unternehmen/internetszene-schweiz-start|publisher=Bilanz|date=8 March 2012|language=German |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926191030/http://www.bilanz.ch/unternehmen/internetszene-schweiz-start|archivedate=26 September 2017}}</ref>  Centralway entered the Swiss market by acquiring an internet agency called Netvision and making it a subsidiary of Centralway, initially called "Centralway Factory", intended to be a [[corporate accelerator]].<ref name=startwerk>{{cite news|title=Internet-investor Martin Saidler: «Wir wollen Startups bauen»|url=https://www.startwerk.ch/2012/03/07/internet-investor-martin-saidler-wir-wollen-startups-bauen/|publisher=Startwerk.ch|date=7 March 2012|language=German |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301005809/https://www.startwerk.ch/2012/03/07/internet-investor-martin-saidler-wir-wollen-startups-bauen/|archivedate=1 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=bilanz2011/><ref>{{cite news|title=Press release: Aus Netvision wird Centralway Factory|url=http://www.werbewoche.ch/medien/2012-03-16/aus-netvision-wird-centralway-factory|date=16 March 2012 |publisher=Werbewoche|language=German |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926235523/http://www.werbewoche.ch/medien/2012-03-16/aus-netvision-wird-centralway-factory|archivedate=26 September 2017}}</ref> The company [[Numbrs Personal Finance AG|Centralway Numbrs]] was founded in the accelerator in 2012 to create an [[Application software|app]] for [[mobile banking]]; its founder was Julien Arnold.<ref>{{cite news|title=7 Questions with Julian Arnold, Founder and CEO of Numbrs|url=http://www.fintecforumdach.de/News_%26_Blogs-e/Eintrage/2013/10/18_7_Questions_with_Julian_Arnold,_Founder_of_Numbrs.html|work=Fintech Forum|date=18 October 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122033507/http://www.fintecforumdach.de/News_%26_Blogs-e/Eintrage/2013/10/18_7_Questions_with_Julian_Arnold,_Founder_of_Numbrs.html|archivedate=22 January 2018}}</ref>

In 2013 Saidler set up a [[venture capital]] fund called Centralway Ventures based in Switzerland but operating in the UK; it made an investment in [[Buttercoin]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lomas|first1=Natasha|title=Swiss Company-Builder Centralway Opens $50M Fund, Invests $250k In Bitcoin Whitelabel Exchange Buttercoin|url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/09/18/centralway-fund-buttercoin-seed/|publisher=Techcrunch|date=18 September 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170706123136/https://techcrunch.com/2013/09/18/centralway-fund-buttercoin-seed/|archivedate=6 July 2017}}</ref>  As of January 2018 the fund was closed down.<ref>{{cite web|title=Centralway Ventures: Private Company Information |accessdate=22 January 2018 |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=246999706 |publisher=Bloomberg||archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122055205/https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=246999706|archivedate=22 January 2018}}</ref>

In 2013, Saidler founded Saidler & Co. as a [[family office]] that operated through three arms; Statmentt, which invested in fintech companies, an investment fund, and a real estate investment fund operating in Switzerland, Austria and Hungary.<ref name=globes-seeks>{{cite news|last1=Tsipori|first1=Tali|title=Swiss entrepreneur seeks Israeli high-tech investments|url=http://www.globes.co.il/en/article-swiss-entrepreneur-seeks-israeli-high-tech-investments-1001192731|publisher=Globes English|date=15 June 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180119120314/http://www.globes.co.il/en/article-swiss-entrepreneur-seeks-israeli-high-tech-investments-1001192731|archivedate=19 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Saidler & Co. United Kingdom Ltd|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/08915774|publisher=Companies House UK|accessdate=22 January 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122055325/https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/08915774|archivedate=January 22, 2018|language=en}}</ref>  Saidler invested in Centralway's businesses through his family office.<ref name=tcdubai>{{cite news|last1=Steve|first1=O'Hear|title=Dubai’s sovereign wealth fund invests in Swiss-made banking app Centralway Numbrs|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/01/10/the-investment-corporation-of-dubai-centralway-numbrs/|publisher=Techcrunch|date=10 January 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180119120226/https://techcrunch.com/2017/01/10/the-investment-corporation-of-dubai-centralway-numbrs/|archivedate=19 January 2018}}</ref> 

The Numbrs app, which aggregated a person's banking and credit card information in one app, was demonstrated at a fintech conference in 2013,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sposito|first1=Sean|title=Reporter's Picks: Three Top Apps at FinovateFall|work=American Banker|date=16 September 2013}}</ref> then launched in Germany in 2014.<ref name=datacenter/>  Centralway began focusing on fintech.<ref name=boersen/><ref name=datacenter>{{cite news|last1=Ostler|first1=Ulrike|title=Software-Hersteller Centralway baut sich eine Bank|url=http://www.datacenter-insider.de/software-hersteller-centralway-baut-sich-eine-bank-a-456227/|publisher=Datacenter-insider.de|date=19 April 2014|language=German |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122055941/https://www.datacenter-insider.de/software-hersteller-centralway-baut-sich-eine-bank-a-456227/|archivedate=22 January 2018}}</ref>  By January 2017 the company said that people had entered about 1.5 million accounts into the Numbrs app and the company had raised about $125 million, and the majority shareholder was Saidler's family office.<ref name=tcdubai/><ref>{{cite news|title=Centralway Looks to Take On UK Banks with App for All Accounts.|publisher=Financial Times|last=Noonan|first=Laura|date=28 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Postbank und Norisbank kooperieren mit Centralway Numbrs|url=http://www.kreditwesen.de/bank-markt/ergaenzende-informationen/bank-markt-meldungen/postbank-norisbank-kooperieren-centralway-numbrs-id37425.html|publisher=Kreditwesen.de|date=26 January 2017|language=German |accessdate=21 January 2018}}</ref>  In June 2017 the company cut about a third of its workforce.<ref name=Hody>{{cite news|last1=Hody|first1=Peter|title=Massenentlassung bei Schweizer Milliarden-Fintech|url=https://www.finews.ch/news/banken/27637-centralway-numbrs-fintech-zuerich-stellenabbau-martin-saidler-entlassungen|work=finews.ch|date=7 June 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180119120321/https://www.finews.ch/news/banken/27637-centralway-numbrs-fintech-zuerich-stellenabbau-martin-saidler-entlassungen|archivedate=19 January 2018|language=de-CH}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Swiss Fintech Giant Cuts a Third of its Jobs|url=https://www.finews.asia/finance/24781-swiss-fintech-giant-cuts-a-third-of-its-jobs|work=Finews|date=7 June 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170714031036/https://www.finews.asia/finance/24781-swiss-fintech-giant-cuts-a-third-of-its-jobs|archivedate=14 July 2017|language=en-gb}}</ref>

In 2015 Saidler started travelling to Israel, seeking investors and investment opportunities in the [[Silicon Wadi|IT sector there]], especially in fintech.  Boaz Barak, whom he knew from the Swiss banking industry, retired to Israel and became Saidler's liaison there.<ref name=globes-seeks/><ref name=globes-when>{{cite news|title=When is a bank not a bank?|url=http://www.globes.co.il/en/article-when-is-a-bank-not-a-bank-1001095558|publisher=Globes Israel|date=18 January 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180119120417/http://www.globes.co.il/en/article-when-is-a-bank-not-a-bank-1001095558|archivedate=19 January 2018}}</ref>

