{{Other people|Hugh Fraser}}
'''Sir Hugh Fraser, 2nd Baronet''' (18 December 1936 – 5 May 1987), formerly '''2nd Baron Fraser of Allander''', was [[chairman]] of the [[House of Fraser]], [[Harrods]], George Outram (company), and [[Whyte and Mackay]]. He lived at [[Mugdock]], near [[Milngavie]], [[Scotland]]. He was the son of [[Hugh Fraser, 1st Baron Fraser of Allander]], and inherited the [[Baron Fraser of Allander|Barony of Fraser of Allander]] on his father's death in 1966, but disclaimed it for life the same year. He has 3 daughters: Patricia, Belinda and Caroline. He was not related to the politician [[Hugh Fraser (British politician)|Sir Hugh Fraser]].

==Career==
Fraser was educated at [[St. Mary's School, Melrose]] and [[Kelvinside Academy]].<ref name="burrowes">{{cite book |last=Burrowes |first=John |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WHfmuGzpjU8C&pg=PT28&lpg=PT28&dq=sir+hugh+fraser+st+mary's+school+melrose&source=bl&ots=wUUTKPIend&sig=hXLkvKSg3N0TnUuYdhvW6sz84tw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjAt_3klfTZAhWE-aQKHVbXBfcQ6AEISjAF#v=onepage&q=sir%20hugh%20fraser%20st%20mary's%20school%20melrose&f=false |title=Glasgow: Tales of the City |publisher=[[Random House]] |year=2011 |page= |isbn=178057343X}}</ref>  He was given an [[honorary doctorate]] by the [[University of Stirling]],<ref name=geo>[http://www.scottish-places.info/people/famousfirst959.html Famous People]</ref> where one of the student residences is now named Fraser of Allander after him. In 1981 he gifted the Mugdock Castle estate (purchased by his father) to the regional council as a [[country park]].<ref>[http://www.mugdock-country-park.org.uk/ Mugdock Castle]</ref>  In 1960, he established the Hugh Fraser Foundation for charitable work.<ref name=story>[http://theglasgowstory.com/image.php?inum=TGSA05107 The Glasgow Story]</ref> He was also a major benefactor to the Glasgow Scout Association and was chairman of [[Dumbarton Football Club]]. 
It was alleged by a [[Five (TV)|Channel 5]] documentary that Fraser put up the money for an attempted abduction of [[Ronnie Biggs]] from Brazil, so the latter could stand trial in Britain for his part in the [[Great train robbery (1963)|Great Train Robbery]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.madfrankiefraser.co.uk/viewpoints/views47.htm|title=Channel 5 scores a bulls-eye|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120717071150/http://www.madfrankiefraser.co.uk/viewpoints/views47.htm|archivedate=17 July 2012}}</ref>

Sir Hugh Fraser died from [[cancer]] in 1987, aged 50.<ref name=story/>

